EZLN agreed to abide by the unilateral ceasefire by the government, but without laying down arms or drawing back troops. At the same time they agreed to start peace negotiations with the government.
The ceasefire was a first step towards new peace negotiations with the government.

With this extension they also proposed a lasting truce and the opening of peace negotiations depending on the government first resolving post-electoral disputes in the states of Chiapas, Veracruz and Tabasco, second acknowledging the government of transition to democracy in Chiapas, and third acknowledging the National Mediation Commission.

The rebels' move appeared to be a response to government moves earlier this week when President Ernesto Zedillo ordered an army pullback in two of the most conflict-ridden zones in Chiapas. It was declared that the ceasefire was a corresponding move to the announcement earlier on Wednesday by the URNG guerilla movement to help peace talks, aiming at ending 35 years of military conflict in Guatemala. A new round of U.N.-mediated peace negotiations to end Guatemala's civil war is due to start next week in Mexico City.

The ceasefire by the URNG guerilla movement was announced to help with peace talk negotiations, and the temporary end to hostilities is the most significant advance towards peace since negotiations began five years ago. A new round of U.N.-mediated peace negotiations to end Guatemala's civil war is due to start next week in Mexico City.

Peace talks between the government and URNG began in April 1991. In December 1996, representatives from the government of Guatemala and the UNRG guerilla signed an agreement that could represent the first step towards peace. The agreement, which was signed after three days of negotiations in Oslo, is called a breakthrough for peace efforts in Guatemala. the definite ceasefire is the outcome of the concluding of the substantive agreements emanating from the peace process.

This ceasefire was declared with hopes to get peace in the country."The presidents are to hold an often-postponed follow-up meeting at the Tesoro Beach resort on El Salvador's Pacific Coast, 60 kms (36 miles) southeast of San Salvador, on Monday and Tuesday to try to revive the stalled peace process. With the Salvadorean conflict intensifying during the past year, the FMLN communique also urged the presidents to discuss a peace plan proposed by the rebels last month.In it the rebels offered to recognise presidential elections if they were postponed from March 19 to September 16 and guarantees taken to ensure free and fair participation of leftist candidates. They broadened the offer on Tuesday by proposing a 60-day ceasefire during the elections." (Reuters News, 08.02.1989)

SAN SALVADOR, March 1, Reuter - Leftist guerrillas refused on Wednesday to call a ceasefire in the war against El Salvador's U.S.-backed government until it agreed on a time and place for peace talks. The rebel announcement followed a night of attacks hours after the armed forces declared a three-month unilateral ceasefire from midnight on Tuesday in what they said was a move to help peace efforts.

"MEXICO CITY, Sept 12, Reuter - Farabundo Marti National Liberation Front (FMLN) guerrilla commanders and a five-member government commission arrived in Mexico City on Tuesday for the first peace talks in two years in El Salvador's decade-long civil war. The talks, due to begin on Wednesday, are the first between the rebels and the rightist government of President Alfredo Cristiani who has said he has given priority to ending the war that has cost 70,000 lives. The last time the rebels met with officials from the Salvadorean government was in October 1987, when talks between the FMLN and then-president Jose Napoleon Duarte ended with little progress made towards ending the bloodshed. The dialogue will take place during a rare unilateral guerrilla ceasefire and a suspension of rebel sabotage, moves the FMLN says are aimed at creating a positive climate for the talks." (Jacobsen, R., 12.09.1989)

cf_pp: The Colombian government and the guerrilla group ELN agreed on 30 March 2016 to launch public peace negotiations. The breakthrough came after more than two years of confidential, exploratory talks in which Norway has assisted. Mediators in the peace process are Brazil, Chile, Cuba, Ecuador, Norway and Venezuela, and negotiations will take place in these Latin American countries. The bilateral ceasefire was agreed during the third round of negotiations in September 2017 in Quito, Ecuador.

"The text of a cease-fire agreement between Azerbaijan and Armenia, signed in Sochi on 19th September, was carried by `Krasnaya Zvezda' on the 23rd. "The text of the agreement was not immediately released but the principal points, in addition to the cease-fire, summarized by participants included a stated resolve to try and disarm all ethnic militias and roaming gangs by Jan. 1. No mechanisms for this have been fashioned yet, but Soviet central military and militia officials reportedly have agreed to a role in the process. A second point is a political agreement to strip away a welter of contradictory executive and military decrees from the union Government and essentially return the situation to the quieter time before 1988. In this, Armenia agreed to renounce its attempt to annex the enclave and Azerbaijan agreed to be more respectful of the home-rule rights of Karabakh's Armenians. The process of self-determination provided in the compact includes province elections, participants said." (The New York Times, 24.09.1991)

"Senior Armenian official has said a peace deal will shortly be signed in Moscow to end the six-year conflict with Azerbaijan over the disputed territory of Nagorno-Karabakh." (Reuters, 15.05.1994)"Under the accords which will be signed by the leaders of the military departments tomorrow [17th May], the lines of contact will be set from which the troops will be withdrawn from 25th May to a distance of 5km to 10km, depending on local conditions. It is intended to create and to set up by 24th May 49 observation posts along the demarcation line. Russian officers will command the posts but their company will comprise representatives of the sides, and possibly of the CIS states and the CSCE. It is proposed that special peacekeeping forces of Russia or the CIS states numbering around 1,800 should be set up to guarantee the safety of the posts. Moreover, a reserve of forces and weapons on the scale of one motor-rifle battalion will be set up." (18.05.1994)

The ceasefire agreed on a month ago gets reaffirmed (CF 3), a positive sign since talks during this month did not really bring any change as rebels and government did not abandon their conditions. Rebels did not agree to deploy ECOWAS troops, but wanted the Senegalese and Guinean troops backing the president removed. Both sides accused the other of violations. The reaffirmed ceasefire also contains plans for further talks in September. However, they still cannot agree on who will be responsible for the monitoring/enforcement. There are also tensions between the mediators, the CPLP and ECOWAS at a later stage.

cf_pp: The new president who came into office in March (Abdoulaye Wade) stated that the solution of the Casamance conflict would be a priority of his government. In this context talks were re-started. Interestingly, Wade refused third party mediation. Yet, the initial peace talks collapsed in December, as the MFDC has to deal with infighting and reshuffling leadership. Finally, the ceasefire is agreed on concurrently with the decisions to start political negotiations two weeks later.

Concurrently with the ceasefire 6 in November 2000 the parties agreed to talks but those never took place due to the continuing violence. This ceasefire is a new intent. It is partly contributing to dismantling the status of war by including economic aid for rebels to be reintegrated into civilian life, freeing of prisoners by both sides, return of refugees and land-mine removal. Furthermore, the agreement includes the restoration of the free-circulation of goods and people, the release of prisoners, infrastructure programs for Casamance and rehabilitation programs for former rebels. The question of autonomy is not tackled.

It is partly contributing to dismantling the status of war by including economic aid for rebels to be reintegrated into civilian life, freeing of prisoners by both sides, return of refugees and land-mine removal. Furthermore, the agreement includes the restoration of the free-circulation of goods and people, the release of prisoners, infrastructure programs for Casamance and rehabilitation programs for former rebels. The question of autonomy is not tackled.

cf_pp: Following a 3-day conference, the rebels declare a month-long unilateral ceasefire and are reported to have agreed on a peace process. It has become increasingly hard for the radical wing to keep fighting because they have less and less resources and public support. The previous years since the last ceasefire were blighted with sporadic violence and reported splits within the MFDC.

Following secret negotiations between rebels and government, a peace accord was reached that appears to definitively end the conflict, although sources indicate that at least 3 rebel factions are unwilling to ratify the agreement. The ceasefire was signed by Senegal's Interior Minister and Senghor Diamacoune in the presence of several cabinet ministers, diplomats and opposition leaders in Ziguinchor. There was an unusually big signing ceremony. The MFDC has committed to drop their quest for independence and to disarm and surrender its weapons to the ICRC and the RADDHO, while the Senegalese government pledged to grant amnesty to ex-combatants and facilitaite their integration to the regular Senegalese army and invest money for the development of Casamance.

cf_pp: The MFDC is highly factionalised especially since the death of former leader Diamacoune Senghor in January 2007 and infighting took place. The insurgency has been ongoing on a low-intensity level. The peace talks with the radical wing initiated with the ceasefire in 2004 broke down in February 2005 and have only resumed in 2013. This ceasefire seems to be a result of these new ongoing peace negotiations: It was declared by Salif Sadio, the leader of the currently most powerful MFDC faction. According to S. Sadio the ceasefire was declared "to give a chance to ongoing peace negotiations over Casamance". In March Cesar Atoute Badiat�, head of the second-most significant faction announced that his group was ready to join negotiations. The Community of Sant'Egidio has been mediating between the government and the MFDC since 2012.

Peace talks have stalled after the breakdown of the ceasefire and fighting continues. New talks were held in September. While the government signs the ceasefire already at the end of September, the oppositon signs only later. However, despite the signing of the ceasefire, heavier fighting than before breaks out the next day. After about a week, Angolan troops support the Cobras and they manage to win the city and dispel the government in mid-October. Then there are no more reports on the conflicts until summer 1998.

In December 1999, there is the first report of a ceasefire that is also framed as a definitive one, since the president even offers rebels amnesty if they turn in their weapons in order to motivate them to sign. At the same time, this offer comes after government troops captured several rebel strongholds. This time, the main rebel leaders seem to be convinced even if they still do not sign as they are in exile.

cf_pp: Peace talks, called the "inter-congolese dialogue" started in Sun City, South Africa, on 25.3.2002 and were suspended a day after due to disagreement of who should be the representative for the political opposition. The government and the RCD also blamed eachother of violating the ceasefire in the southeast of the country. The DRC government delcared a unilateral ceasefire in order to avoid that the clashes between the government, RCD and the Rwandan army have a negative impact on the peace talks, as the RCD threatened to drop out. The talks are sheduled for 45 days and have the goal to establish an interim government which will organize democratic elections.

On 14.3.2002 the Congolese government walked out of the peace talks (inter-congolese dialogue in Sun City) because they accused Rwanda and rebels of new attacks in the city of Moliro (which the government captured in February and subsequently declared a ceasefire CF_ID: 29). After capturing the town of Moliro RCD declared a unilateral ceasefire in order to allow the inter-congolese dialogue to continue and convince the government to join the negotiations again.

This ceasefire between Congo and Rwanda came about after 5 days of negotiations between Rwanda and DRC in South Africa and should bring an end to the reapeted break outs of fighting between DRC and Rwandan rebels in eastern Congo.

This ceasefire between Congo and Rwanda came about after 5 days of negotiations between Rwanda and DRC in South Africa and should bring an end to the reapeted break outs of fighting between DRC and Rwandan rebels in eastern Congo.
This unilateral ceasefire was declared by the Mayi Mayi to allow for the withdrawal of Rwandan troops. At the same time Mayi Mayi is currently negotiating a ceasefire with RCD.

Peace agreement, which results from the inter-congolese dialogue. The agreement was signed in Pretoria, South Africa. It is a comprehensive power-sharing agreement in which parties agree to the establishment of a transitional government until elections are held (incl. transitional constitution). The agreement also renews the commitment of the parties to a ceasefire. It further also calls for the esablishment of a committee for follow-up of the agreement and an international committee. Both of these committees should monitor the implementation of the agreement.
mediator_send: Sir Ketumile Masire (former president of Botswana)

cf_pp: There has been ongoing fighting in the town of Bunia, northeastern Congo. First at the end of February 2003 a ceasefire between two rival rebel groups (UPC, UPDF) should have been signed. This did not take place and the signing of the ceasefire agreement (which included the creation of the Ituri Pacification Commission) was postponed to the 10.3.2003. But on the 10.3.2003 no ceasefire was signed. Finally on the 14.4.2003 Uganda and DRC signed a ceasefire.

There has been ongoing fighting in the town of Bunia, northeastern Congo. First at the end of February 2003 a ceasefire between two rival rebel groups (UPC, UPDF) should have been signed. This did not take place and the signing of the ceasefire agreement (which included the creation of the Ituri Pacification Commission) was postponed to the 10.3.2003. But on the 10.3.2003 no ceasefire was signed. Finally on the 14.4.2003 Uganda and DRC signed a ceasefire.

Clashes were ongoing in the Ituri District, northeastern Congo. The set up of a Ituri Pacification Commission has been discussed for the last few months. This ceasefire is a step towards enabling the set up of this Ituri Pacification Commission. A preparatory commission should be set up two days after the signing of the ceasefire and it will work out a time table for the Ugandan troop withdrawal.

Peace talks between the government and M23 were taking place in Kampala, Uganda. M23 in December 2012 however refused to continue the talks if the government would not sign a formal ceasefire. A second round of talks was scheduled for the beginning of January 2013. The government still refuses to sign a ceasefire but the M23 now announced a unilateral ceasefire and said that it is ready to continue talks.

Peace talks have been ongoing between M23 and the government but no conclusions have been reached so far. On 2.05.13 M23 suspended its participation in the peace process, demanding that the DRC government sign a ceasefire first. At the beginning of this week new fighting broke out. This ceasefire is to allow for a quiet visit of the UN Secretary-General Ban Ki-moon.

M23 declared a unilateral ceasefire after a joint military offensive by the UN combat brigarde and DRC army near Goma. M23 also stated that they were ready for a bilateral ceasefire and for the Kampala peace talks to resume.

This is one of several unilateral ceasefires that have been declared by the M23 this year. M23 seems to declare unilateral ceasefire in particular when they come under military pressure and lose territory under their control. M23 still wants a bilateral ceasefire with the DRC government and peace talks in Kampala. Uganda is on and off.

The head of state from SADC and the International Conference for Great Lakes Region (ICGRL) said at the end of a summit on the security in DRC which took place in South Africa's capital that the M23 must first publicly declare the end to their rebellion before their request for ceasefire and amnesty is accepted by the DRC government. M23 declared an end to its insurgency after a two-week offensive by the DRC government which was supported by the UN combat brigade.

A March 2003 peace accord had reintegrated the Ninjas into the DRC military. The miltia reassembled and started attacking in the Pool region after the presidential elections in April 2016. This ceasefire is the result of several weeks of negotiations between the DRC government and the Ninjas.

Unilateral ceasefire declared by the rebels; signifying wish for dialogue with the government.

Unilateral ceasefire decleared by the rebels; they spoke with religious and council leaders.
Unilateral ceasefire declared by the government in order to facilitate the gathering of the rebels for peace talks. Government forces to leave certain areas.

Extension of the previous offer of ceasefire which aims to allow for the rebels to assemble in designated areas and to meet with the government's peace team. The rebels failed to meet the government at the scheduled meeting and the ceasefire is extended for 5 days to allow for the meeting to take place.
Another extension of the ceasefire in order to allow for rebels to assemble and meet with the government to facilitate peace talks.
7-day unilateral ceasefire declared by the government in response to renewed peace overtures from LRA. Again, conditioned on Rebels assembling in designated areas for the initiation of talks.
After meeting with Niger government representative the rebels state they are going to observe a ceasefire.
Extension of the previous ceasefire to give more time to Lord's Resistance Army rebels to assemble and give them more time to respond ahead of planning peace talks.

Extension of ceasefire first declared by the government of Uganda on 14.11.2004; ceasefire zones created in order to facilitate movement of rebels into specific locations for talks. So far extensions have taken place as the rebels are not all assembling as requested by government but there is ongoing dialogue between the government and rebels.
Ceasefire extension aimed to finalise talks and have peace agreement signed.
Government declared unilateral ceasefire again aimed at signing of peace agreement which was not completed in the last December ceasefire.
One day extension - follow-up agreement
Unilateral ceasefire declared by rebels as peace talks commence in South Sudan. Once again the government is trying to formalise a peace agreement; talks have been ongoing now for some time.
Juba agreement following peace talks between rebels and governenment in Juba, Sudan.
Juba agreement following peace talks between rebels and governenment in Juba, Sudan.
Renewal of the earlier Juba agreement which aimed (as with previous agreements) to assemble rebels in specific zones.

Juba agreement extension to allow for further talks (cannot come to an agreement on certain issues); Continuation of previous cessation of hostilities agreement aimed at getting the LRA rebels to assemble in specific zones. This has repeatedly been extended to give the rebels more time to assemble and to continue dialogue through peace talks.

Resumption of peace talks under the Juba agreement; Rebels sign deal on reconciliation and accountability but talks collapsed when rebels withdrew from the talks.

Resumption of peace talks in Juba - international (US and EU) observers have joined the talks in order to try and urge the rebels to sign a final agreement after dealing with negotiations on a permanent ceasefire as well as DDR.

Stemming from Juba talks, government and rebels sign a 'permanent' truce which will come in to force upon the signing of the final overall 5 point accord. This is set to take place in the coming week.

Chronology: The parties signed the Cessation of Hostility on 26th August 2006; Comprehensive Solutions on 2nd May 2007; Accountability and Reconciliation on 29th June 2007 and implementation of power sharing modalities signed on 22nd February 2008 while permanent ceasefire signed on 23rd February 2008 respectively. Media hails this as the final and permanent ceasefire before peace agreement to be signed between LRA and Ugandan government.

The results of the presidential election in 2007 were disputed and since then violent riots between the supporters of the former president Kibaki and its rival Raila Odinga took place. This is a power-sharing agreement that mainly ended the subnational violence.

The results of the presidential election in 2007 were disputed and since then violent riots between the supporters of the incumbent president Kibaki and its rival Raila Odinga took place. This is a power-sharing agreement that mainly ended the subnational violence.
The Mungiki Sect announced a seven-day strike that was violently imposed but called this off after Prime Minister Odinga announced that the Mungiki "could be productively engaged in nation building".
Declared unilaterally without former consultation with the government, conditioned on non-violent conduct by the army; the army denied to declare a ceasefire because they would not be at war.

The government and the rebels had met for talks in Rome since December 1996 and announced now officially to negotiate a ceasefire later on. The media mainly referred to it as a pre-ceasefire (cf. comments).

Rebels and government agreed on a truce to facilitate further negotiations, the truce resulted from negotiations which started already two years ago. In May 1997, the parties had agreed officially during talks in Rome to negotiate a ceasefire later on (cf. ceasefire 2). The faction CNDD-FDD was not invited to the negotiations. The negotiations took place in Arusha, Tanzania. Mediator was Julius Nyerere.

The rebel faction CNDD-FDD (leadership of (Jean Bosco Ndayikengurukiye) that was part of the peace negotiations under Julius Nyerere declared this unilateral ceasefire due to Nyerere's death. Nyerere was former president of Tanzania and the rebels claimed to cease hostilities out of solidarity with the Tanzanian people.

The CNDD-FDD faction led by Jean Bosco Ndayikengurukiye and the FNL faction of Alain Mugarabona signed the ceasefire in Dar es Salaam, Tanzania during a regional summit on Burundi. Mediator was deputy President of South Africa Jacob Zuma. The groups had not been included in the Arusha Peace Agreement in 2000 and since then negotiations on a ceasefire have continued. The FDD-Ndayikengurukiye had signed a MoU with the government in August 2002 in which they agreed to negotiate a ceasefire. The other, Nkurunziza-led FDD faction and the FNL by Rwasa Agaton did not sign any ceasefire so far.

The Nkurunziza-led FDD faction declared a unilateral suspension of hostilities. At this moment, the faction is negotiating a ceasefire agreement and they would do so to encourage commitment. Earlier, they had called on the government to declare a bilateral suspension of hostilities for the duration of the negotiations. They conditioned the suspension of hostilities on not being attacked by the government forces.

Since October 2002, when two smaller factions signed a ceasefire with the government (Ceasefire 5), negotiations with Nkurunziza-led CNDD-FDD faction and the FNL have continued. The regional heads (Uganda, Tanzania, possibly Kenya) repeatedly extended the deadline to agree on a ceasefire. The Nkurunziza-FDD finally signed a comprehensive ceasefire during a regional summit in the beginning of December (Ceasefire 8). Until the comprehensive version enters into force, a preliminary cessation of hostilities is put in place - this ceasefire 7. Leading mediators were Jakob Zuma (South Africa) and the president of Uganda.

Hence, regional governments threatened to impose sanctions on the group. The FNL rejects to talk with the transitional government but demands the Tutsi military as negotiation partner.
The FNL led by Rwasa had declared a unilateral ceasefire after talks between the government and the FNL had broken down. The government followed the move and also declared a unilateral ceasefire.

This ceasefire refers to the Rwasa Faction of FNL. The ceasefire is not directly connected to talks between the conflict parties. However, committing themselves to a peaceful conduction of the referendum can be understood as willingness to advance the peace process.
The FNL-Rwasa increasingly engaged in talks, especially with the head of the UN mission to Burundi. This ceasefire has been declared after talks with the Tanzanian Foreign Minister.

The fact that the talks were held face-to-face is stressed by the media because Rwasa denied to talk to the Burundian President before. They agreed to conclude a permanent ceasefire within a month.

cf_pp: Following dialogue in Feburary between the presidents of Burundi, Rwanda, Uganda, Tanzania and Zaire as well as the Secretary-General of the Organisation of African Unity (OAU) and representatives of the United Nations High Commissioner for Refugees (UNHCR), and a summit in early March, ceasefire agreed on and direct dialogue between rebels and governmnent to follow.

cf_pp: This 'formal' ceasefire comes after a temporary ceasefire CF_2, agreed at a regional summit in February. Rwanda's ruler Habyarimana, offerd an amnesty for rebels and said any exile who wanted to return home could do so. RPF is sceptical about those pledges, believes reforms to bring in multi-party politics are necessary.
mediator_send: Mobutu Sese Seko (President of Zaire), OAU

cf_pp: Ceasefire accord signed in Tanzania after 3 days of negotiations, temporary ceasefire agreed to start in 5 days and definitive ceasefire from end of July. Political talks are to follow to try to solve deep-rooted differences between the rebels and the government.

Follow-up ceasefire from CF_4, talks on a final peace accord between the government and rebels are to begin in Tanzania on August 10.
Follow-up ceasefire from CF_4, talks on a final peace accord between the government and rebels are to begin in Tanzania on August 10.
Dialogue has broken down since the Arusha agreement CF_5, and violence and hostilities are worsening.
Following rebel unilateral ceasefire, government announces week long unilateral ceasefire to try to revive negotiations.
Violence continues, another unilateral ceasefire declaration made by rebels stating that in order for a ceasefire to continue, government troops must stay put.
Government in response to rebel ceasefire call responds by extending unilateral truce declared on 16.02.1993 CF_7.

Talks have taken place between rebels and government in Dar El Salaam, concluding with the agreement to set a new ceasefire and resumption of further peace talks to try to agree on a political settlement.

Talks have taken place between rebels and government in Dar El Salaam, concluding with the agreement to set a new ceasefire and resumption of further peace talks to try to agree on a political settlement.

Tanzanian Peace Accords signed following extensive talks with the OAU and UN present. A transitional national government was supposed to have been set up two months ago, leading to pluralist elections in 1996; however President is reluctant to give away power.

Following death of Rwandan President, renewed violence and power struggle takes place. Rwandas military and police agree but does not involve presidential guard. Agreement on appointment of interim government.

Peace talks and signing ceremony planned, rebels have declared they are not attending talks and are observing a unilateral ceasefire with demands to the government.

cf_pp: Negotiations took place in Tanzania and ceasefire was due to be signed between the interim government and the rebels (CF_16). However rebels do not sign the agreement and declare their own unilateral ceasefire with conditions. This ceasefire is in response to CF 15.

Fighting between the rebels and government troops is fierce in the Capital Kigali. Ceasefire organised by the UN around the airport in order to allow for humanitarian supplies to be delivered. 15,000 refugees living in the capital.

Rebels state they will only negotiate with the army, and not the interim government as this would amount to recognition of their enemy. Interim government is not permitting talks between Rwandan armed forces and the rebels.

Ceasefire to allow safe visit of UN Envoy who is travelling to Rwanda to hold peace talks.

cf_pp: Humanitarian ceasefire to allow the rescue of orphans. UNAMIR, contacts RPF and secures a ceasefire during the operation which is carried out by French forces.

International actors hoped rebels would agree to a ceasefire with government forces which would allow intervention, mediated by the UN. However, Rebels continue to attack and eventually defeat government forces and declare a unilateral ceasefire and wish to form new government.
FDLR are ex-FAR [former Rwandan army]; Following the surrender of the commander of the FDLR in 2003, as well as many armed groups. This is a declaration of surrender with voluntary disarmamet.

After weeks of fighting between the USC factions of the interim president Ali Mahdi and the general Farah Aideed, they agree to ceasefire. However, it is immediately broken.

When the UN starts to get involved, Aideed first is reluctant to accept a peaceforce and does not see the need for a ceasefire. However, he suddenly declares a unilateral ceasefire, that he almost immeaditely breaks.

After some fruitless efforts of mediation by several IOs, the UN declares an arms embargo and calls for a ceasefire in Somalia. The leaders of the factions agree to the necessity of a ceasefire. However, it takes an invitation to the UN in New York and mediation by several IOs to bring the leaders to sign seperate ceasefire documents since they are reluctant to meet at the same table. A formal ceasefire is planned to be established later. However, fighting continues.
mediator_send: UN, OAU, League of Arab States, the Islamic Conference Organisation

cf_pp: Even after the talks at the UN in NY, fighting continues. Then there is a temporary ceasefire to allow the mediators/peace mission to come to the capital and prepare further talks.
Even after the talks at the UN in NY, fighting continues. Then there is a temporary ceasefire to allow the mediators/peace mission to come to the capital and prepare further talks.

The new ceasefire seems more comprehensive with the leaders agreeing in principle to monitoring by the UN, which Aideed was reluctant to before. However, the exact form of monitoring is left to discuss later and the ceasefire is also immediately violated, by even shelling ships with food supplies. A small unarmed UN observer mission (UNOSOM) is sent to Mogidishu, however Aideed soon threatens to block their deployment since he claims they are biased and supporting the rival factions.
mediator_send: UN, OAU, League of Arab States, the Islamic Conference Organisation

cf_pp: Even though the March ceasefire holds, there is still fighting in the capital and discussions about how many peacekeepers should be deployed and when. With the US intervening before deployment of the UN peacekeeping mission and therefore putting pressure on the fighting parties, another ceasefire was mediated in December and Aideed supports a limited number of peacekeepers being deployed. The ceasefire is mainly humanitarian, but in early January a conference follows where all 14 clans dicuss cessations of hostilities with Aideed being the only one opposing disarmament.

At a conference in Ethiopia with all Somali factions taking part, Aideed agrees to a ceasefire, feeling the pressure by the US-led intervention. His agreement comes in steps: It seems that on January 7, they just call for a ceasefire. On January 11, it seems to start, but afterwards there are reports that Aideed still refuses to sign. On January 15, he finally agrees. However, the exact implementation of the ceasefire is still unclear. There is a peace conference planned for March 15, where negotiations would continue. The ceasefire does not seem mainly humanitarian anymore, but also connected to the peace process. Fighting against the US intervention and rivalries between clans continue, however. In June, the US step up their attacks on Aideed specifically.

After the Islamic courts captured Mogadishu and defeated the alliance of different warlords against terrorism (that was financed by the US), they proclaim a ceasefire with the government. The ceasefire does not include the defeated warlords. Some of them were formely part of the government, but most were excluded after they refused to stop fighting against the Islamic courts. Negotiations between the signatories are planned to begin in mid-July. However, shortly after the signing of the ceasefire, the Islamic courts change their leader to a more fundamentalist one and they violate the ceasefire, endangering peace talks. In September, they agree to join military forces and form an IGAD- and AU-backed committee to observe the implementation of the ceasefire.

After the two sides realise that military victory will be difficult, they engage in UN-brokered talks and agree to a temporary ceasefire and that Ethiopian troops should leave in 120 days provided that UN troops can be deployed instead. Adressing the issue of the Ethiopian troops was a key condition to even participate in talks for the ARS. The Al-Shabab wing of the Islamic courts was not part of the negotiations. Fighting goes on after the meeting since the Ethiopian troops are not part of the agreement and the ARS therefore deems it legitimate to attack them until they leave the country. Darfur Peace Agreement (DPA). Others not included in signing. The largest rebel group, Minni Minnawi's faction of the Sudan Liberation Movement signed the accord. Another faction Abdel Wahid Nur, and the smaller Justice and Equality Movement rejected it. The peace deal caused a complete realignment of Darfur's rebel movement. All those who opposed the agreement are now grouped under a new umbrella organisation calling itself the National Redemption Front. This includes a new rebel faction called the G19, comprised of a group of commanders who broke away from Abdul Wahid's faction of the SLA. The NRF is the main target of the government offensive now underway in Darfur.

South Sudanese President Salva Kiir and SPLM-IO leader have signed an agreement providing to implement a comprehensive and lasting ceasefire in the country ahead of the formation of an inclusive transitional cabinet. The deal was signed at the Sudanese presidency in Khartoum by President Kiir and his rival Machar among vast diplomatic presence. The parties agreed to open the humanitarian corridors, release detainees, withdraw troops and militarily disengage. The agreement calls on the African Union and IGAD to deploy protection forces and ceasefire monitors to observe the ceasefire implementation.

South Sudan's main rivals have signed the long-awaited final peace agreement to end the five-year war in the country. President Salva Kiir and opposition leader Riek Machar late Wednesday [12.09.2018] shook hands after signing the deal in neighbouring Ethiopian capital Addis Ababa. This is the second peace agreement mediated by Igad following round of talks in Khartoum that started in June that led to the signing of a new ceasefire after a face-to-face meeting between President Kiir and Dr Machar.

The local agreement is at the center of President Bashar al-Assad's "national reconciliation" efforts and come as his government is accused of derailing talks between the two sides in the Swiss city of Geneva. Negotiations have gained pace, with ceasefires established in the suburbs of Barzeh, Yarmouk, Beit Sahm and Yalda. Discussions are underway in the opposition bastion of Darayya. As with a similar UN-brokered deal in the city of Homs, residents have been offered a chance to leave the area.

This ceasefire is part of the Doha Peace Process mediated by Qatar. For background evidence see: �Qatari mediation ended this fourth round. In May 2007 Qatari Emir Hamad visited Yemen, and a delegation from the Qatari foreign ministry met with the Houthi leadership. Shortly thereafter Yahya al-Houthi traveled to Qatar. Following these meetings, a list of general principles was created, which led to a ceasefire in mid-June 2007. The Qatari peace plan, called the Doha Agreement, was initially kept secret. It included several broad components, including a government amnesty, the reconstruction of Saada, a commitment by the Houthis to give up their heavy weapons, and the establishment of a committee to work out the specifics of a peace settlement. That committee comprised representatives from the Yemeni government, the Houthis, and the Qatari government. The subsequent agreement included a halt to all military operations, the release of all prisoners within one month, and the establishment of committees to handle compensation and reconstruction. It also called for senior Houthi leaders including Abdul Malik al-Houthi, Abdul Karim al-Houthi, and Abdullah alRuzami to go into permanent exile in Qatar. These were important fi rst steps, although fi ghting in Saada persisted throughout this process. Despite this progress the Doha Agreement failed, because it provided no specifi cs on how to reconstruct Saada or arrange the exile of the senior Houthi leaders, and because of Saudi displeasure at Qatar�s involvement. The Yemeni government also complained that the Qatari mediation efforts led the Houthis to believe that they were equal to the state. The agreement collapsed, but its fundamentals remain the likely basis for any future settlement.� Boucek Christopher (2010) War in Saada: From National Insurrection to National Challenge, Carnegie Endowment, Middle East Program No. 110, pp.7-8

An Afghan Army commander stationed in the deadliest corner of Helmand Province brokered a ceasefire and turf-sharing deal with local Taliban insurgents there, according to government and police officials, in an example of the sort of ground-level bargaining that some see as increasingly likely once international troops withdraw next year. Despite the political sensitivity over such deals, some Afghan commanders and leaders say they may actually be a desirable step toward peace after Western forces withdraw, particularly in highly contested areas like Sangin. Local leaders, in particular, say it is time to start talking, as they are fed up with a war that has caught civilians in the middle.

The new ceasefire has strict rules that it will be terminated if any rebels break it.

The ceasefire has continued into its fourth year, however the shaky ground between the two sides has been largely a product of NDFB's splinter. The ceasefires continue, however formal talks have yet to happen. " Talking to newsmen, NDFB' publicity secretary, Sanjarang told newsmen that the ceasefire pact with Government has entered its fourth year, yet formal political dialogue is yet to start. The political charter of demands has also been submitted to the Centre last September, he added.The NDFB spokesman said that they have urged both Governments of India and Assam to immediately start the political dialogue. The ball is in government's court, he said. On the other hand, the Centre is still disturbed with the ongoing acts of violence indulged by the NDFB." (Assam Tribune 04.07.2009)

ULFA declared a unilateral ceasefire on July 12, 2011, 5 months after an 'icebreaking' meeting with the government of India. This next step to sign a bilateral ceasefire was an indication of both sides looking for a mutually sustainable political solution to the conflict. Few details were described about the actual ceasefire. From statements from the leaders, it is clear that the group will not achieve their demand of an independent state. The group is supposed to stay in designated camps and have their weapons in joint custody during the talks.

This faction of the UPDS has been in talks with the government since its initial ceasefire signed in 2002. Although the group originally demanded a seprate state, this final peace agreement establishes the creation of a territorial council which will be given a total of 29 state subjects and powers to control within the districts under its control. The group had to demobilize within one month, which it did in early December.

After entering into a ceasefire with the government in July of 2004, with extensions and dialogues throughout, both factions of the ANVC have entered into a MoS. "According to the agreement, both groups will be disbanded within three months and their cadres will surrender arms and ammunition to the authorities. The government has agreed to give more powers to the autonomous district council under the Sixth Schedule of the Constitution in the Garo Hills region of Meghalaya. Garo language would be considered as an official language of the state, official sources said. The agreement provides for enhanced autonomy for the Garo Hills Autonomous District Council." The Times of India (25 Septemer 2014)

"According to the terms of the accord, both sides have agreed to confine their respective forces to certain designated areas in Kachin state. The agreement has not been officially announced, and the Kachin rebels insist their truce with Rangoon differs from similar cease-fire agreements reached between the Burmese Government and other ethnic rebels and former communist insurgents in 1989-90. They have called these agreements "business deals," while the recent Rangoon-Kachin truce is supposed to be the first step towards more comprehensive peace talks between Rangoon and all the country's ethnic rebels." Far Eastern Economic review (22 April 1993)

�This agreement also aims to secure an enduring peace based on the principles of dignity and justice, through an inclusive political dialogue process involving all relevant stakeholders.� The Nationwide Ceasefire agreement (15 October 2015)"President Thein Sein, ethnic leaders and international observers lauded the deal, which was more than two years in the making, although seven of the 15 groups invited to sign it refused, citing differences over which stakeholders should be included in the process and mistrust of the government. [...]According to the agreement, the military and armed ethnic group signatories must meet within two weeks of the ceremony to 'define the exact timeframes governing cease-fire related matters and their implementation.' A 'political dialogue,' which may include non-signatory armed groups as observers, will begin within 90 days. Additionally, the government has pledged to remove signatories from a list of 'terrorist groups' in the country, and observers say the cease-fire agreement will open the door to development in their regions." Lat et al. (15 October 2015)

The peace negotiations began in the Philippines in January 1997, continued under the facilitation of the government of Malaysia beginning 2001, and led to the signing of the Framework Agreement on the Bangsamoro in October 2012 and the completion of all its attached documents in January 2014. This Comprehensive Agreement is a product of the pursuit for a solution to the Bangsamoro Question with honor, justice, and dignity for all concerned. It ends the armed hostilities between the two arties and provides for the negotiated political settlement of the Bangsamoro Question, thereby ending the armed conflict between the GPH and the MILF, and promoting peace and stability in this part of the world. "The Parties express their gratitude to the very important role of: 1. Malaysia, as the Third-Party Facilitator and Head of Mission of the International Monitoring Team (IMT)." UN Peacemaker (27 March 2014)
